<ns0:eml xmlns:ns0="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.1" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" packageId="hcme.8.5" scope="system" system="knb" xsi:schemaLocation="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.1 eml.xsd"><dataset scope="document"><title>Organic Matter Accumulation in the Forest Floors of Forest Ecosystems in Taiwan-soil analysis</title><creator id="1164788145458" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Huang</givenName><surName>Chu-Meei</surName></individualName><organizationName>Taiwan Forestry Research Institute</organizationName><positionName>Assistant Researcher</positionName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>53 Nan Hai Road</deliveryPoint><city>Taipei</city><postalCode>100</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">23039978 ext 2903</phone><electronicMailAddress>hcme@serv.tfri.gov.tw</electronicMailAddress></creator><associatedParty id="1164788274597" scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Duh</givenName><surName>Chin-Tzer</surName></individualName><organizationName>Taiwan Forestry Research Institute</organizationName><positionName>Assistant Researcher</positionName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>53 Nan Hai Road</deliveryPoint><city>Taipei</city><postalCode>100</postalCode><country>Taiwan</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">23039978 ext 2906</phone><electronicMailAddress>Gisdu@serv.tfri.gov.tw</electronicMailAddress><role>Content Provider</role></associatedParty><abstract><para>Organic matter accumulation in the forest floors is important for carbon and nutrient storage and cycling in forest ecosystems. In the winter of 2001, forest floors were sampled in 7 major forest types of mountainous areas of Taiwan: Taiwan red pine, Taiwania, China-fir, Crptomeria, Taiwan red cypress, natural broad-leaved and coniferous forests. Results shows that organic matter accumulation of these 7 forest types increased with an increase in elevation, except the O2 layers of Taiwania and O1 layers of natural coniferous forests which showed an opposite trend. Adding stand age to the regression equations  increased the predictive capability of the regression equations based on elevation only. The regression equations developed in this study can be used along with the tree aboveground biomass derived from forest timber surveys to estimate the regional forest aboveground biomass and carbon accumulation in Taiwan.</para></abstract><keywordSet><keyword>aboveground biomass</keyword><keyword>forest type</keyword><keyword>forest floor</keyword></keywordSet><coverage scope="document"><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>Taiwan</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>119.125</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>121.5</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>25.75</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>21.75</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates></geographicCoverage><temporalCoverage scope="document"><singleDateTime><calendarDate>2001</calendarDate></singleDateTime></temporalCoverage></coverage><contact scope="document"><references>1164788145458</references></contact><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Analysis</title><para>Plantations of Taiwan red pine, Taiwania, Cryptomeria, China-fir, and Taiwan red cypress were selected from working circles of Taiwan Forestry Bureau, based on the plantation data bank of the Bureau.The samples were dried at 65oC to constant weight after transported back to the laboratory.</para></section></description><instrumentation>Electronic balance</instrumentation><instrumentation>oven</instrumentation></methodStep></methods><access authSystem="knb" order="denyFirst" scope="document"><allow><principal>public</principal><permission>read</permission></allow></access><dataTable id="1164958141560" scope="document"><entityName>Organic Matter Accumulation EMLdata-H.csv</entityName><entityDescription /><physical id="1164958138279" scope="document"><obje